  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.10181" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Kertch, August 1. 1895.</dateline>
        <opener>Dear Sir,</opener>
        <p>I am much obliged to you for your kind letter of the 11<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> ult.° My Georgian studies have not by any means progressed so far as you seem to think. In 1887 I wrote a little book of travel called „The Kingdom of Georgia“<note
            n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.4523">John Oliver Wardrop, <hi
                  rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Kingdom of Georgia: travel in a land of women, wine and song</hi>, London: Sampson, Low, Marston, Searle &amp;amp; Rivington, 1888.</ref>
            </bibl>

          </note>, which is now out of print, but I have given orders that a bound copy of the rough proofs should be sent to you from England, if this can be found. Last year I published in Boston a translation of Professor Tsagareli’s <pb
            facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/> Catalogue of the Georgian MSS. in Jerusalem: I send you a copy.<note n="2"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref
                  target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8251">A. A. Tsagareli / John Oliver Wardrop, <hi
                  rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
Professor Tsagareli’s Catalogue of the Georgian Manuscripts in the Monastery of the Holy Cross at Jerusalem</hi>, Sankt Petersburg, 1889</ref>
            </bibl> (Svyedyeniya o pamyatnikakh Gruzinskoi Pismennosti) [Erstveröffentlichung in <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Journal of Biblical Literature</hi>, 12].</note> I also published a translation of Saba Orbeliani’s „Book of Wisdom and Lies“ (<foreign
            xml:lang="ka">წიგნი სიბრძნე სიცრუისა</foreign>), published in an <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">editon de luxe</hi> by Mr. William Morris, but I hear that it is exhausted.<note n="3"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8252">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The book of wisdom and lies</hi> / [Verf.:] Sulkhan - Saba Orbeliani. Transl. by Oliver Wardrop, Hammersmith: Kelmscott Press, London: Bernard Quaritch, (1894).</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> My sister has translated a collection of Georgian „Folk Tales“ (publ.<hi
            rendition="#sup">
d</hi> by David Nutt)<note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8253">Marjory Wardrop (transl.), Georgian folk tales, London: D. Nutt, 1894.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note>, and she is now seeking to print a verse translation of Dchavdchavadze’s „Hermit“<note n="5"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8254">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Hermit: a legend</hi>, by Ilia Chavchavadze; translated from the Georgian, by Marjory Wardrop, London: Bernard Quaritch, 1895.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> (<foreign xml:lang="ka">
განდეგილი</foreign>) &amp;amp; other poems.</p>
        <p>My friend C. Dodashvili printed in <foreign
            xml:lang="ka">მანდემილი</foreign> an intresting grammatical sketch<note n="6" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Nicht identifiziert; möglicherweise ein Verwandter oder Nachfahr von <persName>Salomon Dodashvili</persName> (1805-1836), georgischer Philosoph, Lehrer, Journalist und Belletrist.</note> which I had completely translated. Unfortunately, my ms. seems to have been lost or stolen during my journey to the Crimea. I should recommend you to write to Dodashvili <pb
            facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/> for information about grammatical questions. His address is:</p>
        <p>Тифлись</p>
        <p>Kbaшbemckaя цepкobь</p>
        <p>Koncmaнmuнy Дeoдaшbuam.<note n="7" place="foot" type="editorial">Es ist keine Korrespondenz mit Schuchardt erhalten.</note>
        </p>

        <p>It is difficult to get the older books you mention, but if you apply to the Tpybuнckoe Издameлъckoe Тobapщecmbo in <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6084">Tiflis</placeName> I think they could send you the grammars of Cliphiani<note
            n="8" place="foot" type="editorial">Lesart unsicher; Autor nicht nachgewiesen.</note>, Antoni<note n="9"
            place="foot" type="editorial">Zu den kaum zu verifizierenden Literaturangaben vgl. <bibl>
              <ref
                  target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.365">Schuchardt, „Kharthwelische Sprachwissenschaft I“, <hi
                  rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
Wiener Zeitschrift für die Kunde des Morgenlandes</hi> 10, 1896, 115-128</ref>
            </bibl>.</note>, Zordania<note n="10" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.4491">F. Žordania, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Kʿartʿuli grammatika (etimologia da sintakʿsi)</hi>, Tpilisi (Tiflis): Ḥeladze, 1889.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> and the 1886 edition of Chubinov’s dictionary (Georgian-Russian &amp;amp; Russ. Georgian)<note n="11"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.4469">Davit‘ Č'ubinašvil, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">K̕art̕ul-rusuli lek̕sikoni</hi>, Sanktpeterburg: Tipogr. Imperatorskoj Akademīi Naukʺ, 1887.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> which is much better than the 1840 bilingual lexicon.<note n="12" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.4468">David Čubinov, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Gruzinsko-russko-francuzskij slovar</hi>, Sankt-Peterburg: Tip. Imp. Akad. Nauk, 1840.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> Though is has still many faults.</p>
        <p>
          <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2890">
Tsagareli</persName>
          <note n="13" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2890">Alexander Tsagareli</persName> (1844-1929), Prof. der Linguistik in St. Petersburg und Mitbegründer der staatl. Univ. in <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6084">Tiflis</placeName>.</note> was here with us in Kertch about a fortnight ago, and stayed three days, on his way to Kislovodsk.<note
            n="14" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Kislowodsk ist eine Stadt mit 128.553 Einwohnern in der Region Stawropol in Russland. Sie liegt im nördlichen Kaukasus rund 234 Kilometer von der Regionshauptstadt Stawropol (<ref target="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kislowodsk">wikipedia</ref>)</note>
          <pb facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/> He, like all his Countrymen, rejoices to see that you are seriously occupying yourself with the language.</p>
        <p>The lack of intelligible grammars and philological works on <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.742">Georgian</ref> is the chief cause why so little is known of the language and literature in Europe. The beginner has to depend almost entirely on <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.4592">Brosset</persName>, who is nearly worthless.<note n="15"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.4592">Marie Ivanovich Brosset</persName> (1802-1880), franz. Linguist u. Orientalist, der auch Arbeiten zum <ref
              target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.742">
Georgischen</ref> und <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.883">Armenischen</ref> veröffentlichte.</note>
        </p>
        <closer>
          <salute>I look forward with pleasure to the receipt of your works</salute>
          <lb/>
          <salute>Beleave me, dear Sir,</salute>
          <lb/>
          <salute>Very Sincerely Yours,</salute>
          <lb/>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2975">Oliver Wardrop</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
    </body>
